<font face=Arial,Helvetica>
<b>NYC to privatize worst schools</b><br><font face=Arial,Helvetica size=1>Posted on  Tuesday, August 01 @ 03:26:10 EDT

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td bgcolor=ffffff>
<font face=Arial,Helvetica>
<a href=search.php3?query=&topic=13&author=><img src=images/topics/school_bus.jpg border=0 Alt="Education" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10></a>
<P>According to this <A href="http://www.nytimes.com/library/national/regional/072700ny-levy-edu.html">NY Times story</A> (free registration required), New York City plans to hand over control of some of its worst-performing public schools to private companies or nonprofit agencies in the fall of 2001, the first such effort in the city's history and one of the largest programs to privatize education in the country.</P>

<P>Maybe it's just the way this article is written, but this plan sounds surprisingly non-controversial and non-politicized.  I think its great that private, nonprofit organizations are going to be managing some schools, as well as for-profit companies.  Isn't that how most schools used to be run - as private, nonprofit institutions?   I don't know very much about the history of our educational system - perhaps someone else can shed some light on this.</P> 
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
